THOUGHT

The evidence is now consistent and sufficient: the long command-line argument is stored directly in `filelist` in `main`, then `main` calls `comprexx(fileptr)`. Inside `comprexx`, `tempname` is a fixed 1024-byte stack buffer, but line 886 copies the entire user-supplied filename with unbounded `strcpy`. ASan reports a 1101-byte write into `tempname[1024]`, with the overflow starting exactly at the end of the stack object. The surrounding source also shows this file-path handling style is repeated with global `ofname[MAXPATHLEN]`, recursive `nbuf[MAXPATHLEN]`, and several `strcat` calls, so a complete hardening should address the pathname abstraction globally rather than only this one `strcpy`.

ROOT CAUSE: `compress42.c:886` in `comprexx()` declares `char tempname[MAXPATHLEN]` where `MAXPATHLEN` is 1024, then executes `strcpy(tempname, *fileptr)` on a command-line filename whose length is not validated by `main()` or `comprexx()`. When the input argument is 1024 bytes or longer including the terminating NUL requirement, `strcpy` writes past the end of `tempname`, corrupting adjacent stack data / return state. This is why the ASan report shows a stack-buffer-overflow in `comprexx`, with `tempname` occupying stack offsets `[32,1056)` and the write continuing at offset `1056`.

LOCAL FIX: Reject overlong pathnames before copying, and also guard local suffix construction so the fix does not merely move the overflow to the later `.Z` appends/copies. Minimal replacement near the start of `comprexx()`:
```diff
@@ void comprexx(fileptr)
        int     fdout;
        char    tempname[MAXPATHLEN];

+       if (strlen(*fileptr) >= sizeof(tempname)) {
+               fprintf(stderr, "%s: pathname too long\n", *fileptr);
+               exit_code = 1;
+               return;
+       }
        strcpy(tempname,*fileptr);
```
Then, before any `strcat(tempname, ".Z")` or `strcpy(ofname, tempname); strcat(ofname, ".Z");`, require room for the suffix and NUL, for example:
```c
if (strlen(tempname) > sizeof(tempname) - sizeof(".Z")) {
    fprintf(stderr, "%s: filename too long to tack on .Z\n", tempname);
    exit_code = 1;
    return;
}
```
and similarly ensure `strlen(tempname) < sizeof(ofname)` before `strcpy(ofname, tempname)` and `strlen(tempname) <= sizeof(ofname) - sizeof(".Z")` before appending `.Z`. Prefer `snprintf`/checked helper functions over raw `strcpy`/`strcat`, but do not silently truncate filenames.

GLOBAL FIX: Replace ad-hoc fixed-size C pathname buffers plus raw string APIs with a single checked pathname-building abstraction used everywhere in the program. For example, introduce helper functions such as `path_copy(dst, dstsz, src)`, `path_append_suffix(dst, dstsz, suffix)`, and `path_join(dst, dstsz, dir, base)` that return failure on overflow and centralize error reporting. Then ban direct `strcpy`/`strcat` for path manipulation in `compress42.c` and convert `tempname`, `ofname`, and recursive `nbuf` construction to these helpers. Even better structurally, store filenames as dynamically allocated strings sized from `strlen()`/`malloc()` and perform explicit length checks only at OS-call boundaries. This prevents the entire class of stack/global fixed-buffer overflows and inconsistent path-length checks, including the current command-line case and the recursive directory-building case.

